Trump and the Economy
New York — The financial markets finally woke up to the realization that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured two years of unfiltered tweets and public statements from the most powerful person in the world, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On the one hand, so far, investors have been treating Trump as a lightning rod without any rain—meaning they have reacted strongly to his rhetoric but have not seen tangible results.
They would be willing to grant him the benefit of the doubt as long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders.
Many believe that, in the end, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies remain within bounds.
This assumption was more or less confirmed during the first year of Trump's presidency, a period during which economic growth and expected increases in corporate profits—due to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation—led to strong stock market performance.
In 2017, the U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation turned sharply downward, especially in the last few months.
Although company profits rose by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated up and down for most of the year and is now sharply declining.
Currently, various indices are within their correction range (a decline of 10% from their most recent high), with technology stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) having already fallen into a bear market (a decline of 20% or more).
Although increased market volatility reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies as well as key emerging markets, recent turbulence is due to Trump.
At the start of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which raised long-term interest rates and pushed the economy, already near full employment, to its peak.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% triggered the first safe-haven flow of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important U.S. trade partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching a new peak.
Recent actions by the United States toward China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may lead to stagflation (weakened growth and increased inflation).
After all, Trump prepared to restrict the inflow of foreign direct investment and implemented extensive immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of labor supply in the context of increasingly severe labor aging and skill mismatches.
In addition, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan aimed at stimulating private-sector productivity or accelerating the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump has continuously criticized companies' hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially tech companies, which have already faced widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been affected by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening raised both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies faced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies that are heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade ties to China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy created volatility.
The United States' reinstatement of sanctions on Iran pushed up oil prices. Subsequently, the U.S. government revoked exemptions, threatening Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, which led to a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers have benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of American energy companies have finally collapsed.
In addition, excessive fluctuations in oil prices are detrimental to both producers and consumers because they hinder informed investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it's clear that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may slow down quickly, further affecting the economy.
However, the primary cause of the recent quarter's sharp decline in both the U.S. and global stock markets was Trump's own remarks and actions.
Worse than the significant risk of erupting into a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) was Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His attacks began in the spring of 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate exceeded 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the market became skittish when the Fed correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while also signaling that it would hike rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance is a response to Trump's attacks on it.
Faced with hostile tweets from the president, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless Mexican border wall, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move put the market into a state of near panic, and soon after the government shutdown, reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn the market correction into a full-blown crash.
Ahead of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the markets.
He claimed that Trump did not dismiss Powell's plan, the U.S. fiscal situation is good, and this恰恰 highlights the question of whether the situation is truly good.
Recent personnel changes within the government, which may not necessarily affect economic decisions, have also raised concerns in the market.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and the Trump administration will no longer have any sane individuals.
The rest will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead.
The possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical confrontation with China cannot yet be ruled out.
A new Cold War is likely to lead to deglobalization, disrupt global supply chains, but the technology sector will be hit hardest. Recent cases such as ZTE and Huawei serve as clear examples of this.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO during a period of economic and political instability in Europe.
Special prosecutor Robert Mueller's investigation into the relationship between Trump's 2016 campaign and Russia served as a Damocles sword hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of the financial markets.
Like the paranoid madmen in Stanley Kubrick's classic films, he was trapped in a cycle of mutually assured economic destruction.
Nowadays, the market has recognized this danger, with the risk of financial crisis and global recession rising steadily.
